de-42b6-b60a-23bdf883c851","name":"core/heading","attributes":{"content":"A New Threat to the U.S. ","level":2,"id":"a-new-threat-to-the-u-s"},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"f8c4c26c-35d4-4994-a9aa-63f87f7775e7","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"For the American officials, the urgency of the situation stemmed from the fact that the nuclear-armed Cuban missiles were being installed so close to the U.S. mainland–just 90 miles south of \u003ca href=\"https://www.history.com/topics/us-states/florida\"\u003eFlorida\u003c/a\u003e. From that launch point, they were capable of quickly reaching targets in the eastern U.S. If allowed to become operational, the missiles would fundamentally alter the complexion of the nuclear rivalry between the U.S. and the Union of Soviet Socialist Republics (USSR), which up to that point had been dominated by the Americans.","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"dc33afae-6184-4939-a309-924b5157c9f8","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"Soviet leader \u003ca href=\"https://www.history.com/topics/cold-war/nikita-sergeyevich-khrushchev\"\u003eNikita Khrushchev\u003c/a\u003e had gambled on sending the missiles to Cuba with the specific goal of increasing his nation’s nuclear strike capability. The Soviets had long felt uneasy about the number of nuclear weapons that were targeted at them from sites in Western Europe and Turkey, and they saw the deployment of missiles in Cuba as a way to level the playing field. Another key factor in the Soviet missile scheme was the hostile relationship between the U.S. and Cuba. The Kennedy administration had already launched one attack on the island–the failed \u003ca href=\"https://www.history.com/topics/cold-war/bay-of-pigs-invasion\"\u003eBay of Pigs invasion\u003c/a\u003e in 1961–and Castro and Khrushchev saw the missiles as a means of deterring further U.S. aggression.","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"064f26e2-2709-402b-8df0-38b4ae386a9b","name":"core/c