ons that stretched on for nearly a week, they came up with a variety of options, including a bombing attack on the missile sites and a full-scale invasion of Cuba. But Kennedy ultimately decided on a more measured approach. First, he would employ the U.S. Navy to establish a blockade, or quarantine, of the island to prevent the Soviets from delivering additional missiles and military equipment. Second, he would deliver an ultimatum that the existing missiles be removed.","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"c9022509-4e22-4dbd-9f7c-8c9b3e5c5d68","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"In a television broadcast on October 22, 1962, the president notified Americans about the presence of the missiles, explained his decision to enact the blockade and made it clear that the U.S. was prepared to use military force if necessary to neutralize this perceived threat to national security. Following this public declaration, people around the globe nervously waited for the Soviet response. Some Americans, fearing their country was on the brink of nuclear war, hoarded food and gas.","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"b3cdcb08-f677-4075-b6e3-dbad753ab419","name":"corpnews-blocks/banner","attributes":{"heading":"HISTORY Vault: Nuclear Terror","text":"\u003cp\u003eNow more than ever, terrorist groups are obtaining nuclear weapons. With increasing cases of theft and re-sale at dozens of Russian sites, it's becoming more and more likely for terrorists to succeed.\u003c/p\u003e","bgMediaID":42713,"bgMediaURL":"https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2023/03/Nuclear_Terror_3840x2160_NT-scaled-2.jpeg","ctaEnabled":true,"ctaURL":"https://watch.historyvault.com/specials/nuclear-terror-host-arthur-kent","ctaButtonText":"WATCH NOW","ctaNewTab":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"70c7c43b-30ed-4917-b8b7-f8067c66ee8f","name":"core/heading","attributes":{"content":"Showdown at Sea: U.S. Blockades Cuba","level":2,"id":"showdown-at-sea-u-s-blockades-cuba"},"in