d on for nearly a week, they came up with a variety of options, including a bombing attack on the missile sites and a full-scale invasion of Cuba. But Kennedy ultimately decided on a more measured approach. First, he would employ the U.S. Navy to establish a blockade, or quarantine, of the island to prevent the Soviets from delivering additional missiles and military equipment. Second, he would deliver an ultimatum that the existing missiles be removed.","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"c9022509-4e22-4dbd-9f7c-8c9b3e5c5d68","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"In a television broadcast on October 22, 1962, the president notified Americans about the presence of the missiles, explained his decision to enact the blockade and made it clear that the U.S. was prepared to use military force if necessary to neutralize this perceived threat to national security. Following this public declaration, people around the globe nervously waited for the Soviet response. Some Americans, fearing their country was on the brink of nuclear war, hoarded food and gas.","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"b3cdcb08-f677-4075-b6e3-dbad753ab419","name":"corpnews-blocks/banner","attributes":{"heading":"HISTORY Vault: Nuclear Terror","text":"\u003cp\u003eNow more than ever, terrorist groups are obtaining nuclear weapons. With increasing cases of theft and re-sale at dozens of Russian sites, it's becoming more and more likely for terrorists to succeed.\u003c/p\u003e","bgMediaID":42713,"bgMediaURL":"https://assets.editorial.aetnd.com/uploads/2023/03/Nuclear_Terror_3840x2160_NT-scaled-2.jpeg","ctaEnabled":true,"ctaURL":"https://watch.historyvault.com/specials/nuclear-terror-host-arthur-kent","ctaButtonText":"WATCH NOW","ctaNewTab":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"70c7c43b-30ed-4917-b8b7-f8067c66ee8f","name":"core/heading","attributes":{"content":"Showdown at Sea: U.S. Blockades Cuba","level":2,"id":"showdown-at-sea-u-s-blockades-cuba"},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"ebda2abe-42d4-4be5-be87-d643264d01dc","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"A crucial moment in the unfolding crisis arrived on October 24, when Soviet ships bound for Cuba neared the line of U.S. vessels enforcing the blockade. An attempt by the Soviets to breach the blockade would likely have sparked a military confrontation that could have quickly escalated to a nuclear exchange. But the Soviet ships stopped short of the blockade.","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"0649a6fd-5571-4560-b279-9c161c5e38f8","name":"core/paragraph","attributes":{"content":"Although the events at sea offered a positive sign that war could be averted, they did nothing to address the problem of the missiles already in Cuba. The tense standoff between the superpowers continued through the week, and on October 27, an American reconnaissance plane was shot down over Cuba, and a U.S. invasion force was readied in Florida. (The 35-year-old pilot of the downed plane, Major Rudolf Anderson, is considered the sole U.S. combat casualty of the Cuban missile crisis.) “I thought it was the last Saturday I would ever see,” recalled U.S. Secretary of Defense Robert McNamara (1916-2009), as quoted by Martin Walker in “The Cold War.” A similar sense of doom was felt by other key players on both sides.","dropCap":false},"innerBlocks":[]},{"clientId":"a839a309-b448-46ac-8815-de1c55b80113","name":"corpnews-blocks/story-grid","attributes":{"posts":"[{\"id\":21086,\"link\":\"https://www.history.com/news/cuban-missile-crisis-timeline-jfk-khrushchev\",\"title\":\"Key Moments in the Cuban Missile Crisis\",\"type\":\"story\"},{\"id\":32444,\"link\":\"https://www.history.com/news/timeline-us-cuba-relations\",\"title\":\"A Timeline of US-Cuba Relations\",\"type\":\"story\"},{\"id\":34435,\"link\":\"https://www.history.com/news/kennedy-krushchev-vienna-summit-meeting-1961\",\"title\":\"JFK Was Completely Unprepared For His Summit with Khrushchev\",\"type\":\"story\"}]","className"